  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Peripatetic philosopher, c. 371/0-287/6 BC, pupil
        and successor of Aristotle....T., born in Eresus on Lesbos, is said to have been a pupil of
        Alcippus... T.'s many interests are reflected in a list of 225 titles in Diog. Laert.
        5,42-50. There can thus be no doubt of T.'s productivity. Surviving works include two
        important treatises on botany (&#x3A0;&#x3B5;&#x3C1;&#x1F76; &#x3C6;&#x3C5;&#x3C4;&#x1FF6;&#x3BD; &#x1F31;&#x3C3;&#x3C4;&#x3BF;&#x3C1;&#x3AF;&#x3B1;/Per&#xEC; phyt&#xF4;n histor&#xED;a/Historia plantarum;
        &#x3C6;&#x3C5;&#x3C4;&#x3B9;&#x3BA;&#x1FF6;&#x3BD; &#x3B1;&#x1F30;&#x3C4;&#x3AF;&#x3B1;&#x3B9;/phytik&#xF4;n ait&#xED;ai/De causis plantarum) [4; 5; 6]. Several works of differing
        scope deal with human physiology (sweat, signs of fatigue, dizziness; cf. [7; 8; 9]), with
        fish, smells, fire, winds, meteorology (only preserved in Arabic and perhaps incomplete) and
        stones [10; 11; 12; 13; 14; 15]. A treatise on metaphysics also survives, as does a
        doxographical work on sensual perception [16; 17; 18]. His well-known book on the human
        characters (&#x1F28;&#x3B8;&#x3B9;&#x3BA;&#x3BF;&#x1F76; &#x3C7;&#x3B1;&#x3C1;&#x3B1;&#x3BA;&#x3C4;&#x1FC6;&#x3C1;&#x3B5;&#x3C2;, Ethiko&#xEC; Charakt&#xEA;res) became the inspiration for the literary
        genre of the 'character study' in the 17th cent. [19; 20]. Little is known of T. today: most
        of his works are lost..." Fortenbaugh, William W. "Theophrastus." Brill's New Pauly.
        Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and ; Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2010. Brill
        Online. Tufts University Library. 08 October 2010 </mads:note>
